	<text>
		<body>
			<pb n="1"/>
				<p rend="align(right)"><placeName>New Orleans</placeName> <date>April 3<hi rend="sup">rd</hi> 1857</date></p>
				<p>Friend <addressee>Leeser</addressee></p>
			<p rend="indent(2)">Rev &#38; Dear Sir</p>
			<p rend="indent(5)">no doubt<lb/> ere this reach you you are in receipt of<lb/> the papers of yesterday which I sent you each<lb/> containing the account of the Consecration<lb/> of the new Synagogue all that I could say could<lb/> not add to it  It was a scene that all<lb/> creeds must have felt proud to witness every<lb/> nook &#38; corner of the Building was occupied in<lb/> fact it was a sea of Human beings such was<lb/> the demands for tickets of <sic>addmission</sic> that<lb/> a large number of our own persuasion<lb/> &#38; many Hundreds of our Citizens were presented<lb/> from attending <sic>oweing</sic> to every place<lb/> being given out some day prior to the<lb/> consecration  I also sent you the little Book<lb/> was <sic>was</sic> freely distributed to every one present<lb/> containing the proceedings The Choir sang<lb/> beautifully accompanied by a Melodeon &#38; full<lb/> Orchestra the sermon of <persName>Mr Gutheim</persName> was<lb/> as you may have anticipated from the learned<lb/> Gentleman exceedingly interesting &#38; seemed to<lb/> entrance the whole of the large assembly there<add>&#63;</add><lb/> His discourse being twice as long I feel<lb/> confident none would have tired.  I have</p>
			<pb n="2"/>
				<p>as your agent requested the talented Minister<lb/> to furnish me a copy for your Magazine<lb/> I addressed him a note on the subject<lb/> last evening but no reply yet received<lb/> should the he comply I shall immediately<lb/> forward it to you <add>&#63;</add> delivers extempore<lb/> it may be some few days ere I obtain<lb/> it or his refusal as If I must ask<add>&#63;</add> not<lb/> He does not care about publishing his<lb/> sermons&#8212;after the services were concluded<lb/> nearly the whole of His Congregation &#38; many<lb/> of the <placeName>Rampart St</placeName> Synagogue paid their<lb/> respects to him at his splendidly furnished<lb/> Dwelling <sic>anexd</sic> to the Synagogue.  The House<lb/> was brilliantly lit up with Gas &#38; mine Host<lb/> not unprepared for his Guests&#44; who one &#38; all<lb/> did full Justice to the plentiful supply<lb/> of <sic>champaigne</sic> &#38; other good things <del>&#63;</del><lb/>  Take it in all it was an event that will<lb/> live long in pleasant memory to all who<lb/> were so fortunate as to be present  The officers<lb/> of the Congregation deserve much credit<lb/> for the credible manner in which every<lb/> thing was arranged &#38; carried out</p>
				<p>I noticed among the audience a large number<lb/> of our Oldest  citizens with their families<lb/> of our course <persName>Mr Sheppard</persName> the old friend of<lb/> the late <persName>Judah Touro</persName> was among the rest<lb/> nothing further to add but remain</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)">Yours Truly</p>
			<p rend="indent(10)"><persName role="author">Isaac Hart</persName></p>
		</body>
